y Collections\']',4,2,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=LBZbAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','en'),(2504,'How to Read a Poem','[\'Terry Eagleton\']','Wiley-Blackwell','2006-10-20','Lucid, entertaining and full of insight, How To Read A Poem is designed to banish the intimidation that too often attends the subject of poetry, and in doing so to bring it into the personal possession of the students and the general reader. Offers a detailed examination of poetic form and its relation to content. Takes a wide range of poems from the Renaissance to the present day and submits them to brilliantly illuminating closes analysis. Discusses the work of major poets, including John Milton, Alexander Pope, John Keats, Christina Rossetti, Emily Dickinson, W.B. Yeats, Robert Frost, W.H.Auden, Seamus Heaney, Derek Mahon, and many more. Includes a helpful glossary of poetic terms.',9781405151412,'[\'Literary Criticism\']',1,1,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=mU7FZ7W-TkoC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','en'),(2505,'The Gatekeeper','[\'Terry Eagleton\']','Macmillan','2003-06-02','An Oxford scholar and author of The Truth About the Irish candidly recounts his experiences as an impoverished youth, a convent gatekeeper, a Catholic in Protestant England, a working-class Irish immigrant among the Oxbridge elite, and a Marxist visiting professor in Mormon Utah. Reprint. 15,000 first printing.',9780312316136,'[\'Biography & Autobiography\']',4,1,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=93Q0Q1bjH3AC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','en'),(2506,'The Ideology of the Aesthetic','[\'Terry Eagleton\']','Wiley-Blackwell','1991-01-08','The Ideology of the Aesthetic presents a history and critique of the concept of the aesthetic throughout modern Western thought. As such, this is a critical survey of modern Western philosophy, focusing in particular on the complex relations between aesthetics, ethics and politics. Eagleton provides a brilliant and challenging introduction to these concerns, as characterized in the work of Kant, Schiller, Schopenhauer, Kierkegaard, Marx, Nietzsche, Freud, Heidegger, Lukacs, Adorno, Habermas, and others. Wide in span, as well as morally and politically committed, this is Terry Eagleton\'s major work to date. It forms both an original enquiry and an exemplary introduction.',9780631163022,'[\'Literary Criticism\']',3,5,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=QzYDaoaUyLYC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','en'),(2507,'Marxism and Literary Criticism','[\'Terry Eagleton\']','Psychology Press','2002','Is Marx relevant any more? Why should we care what he wrote? What difference could it make to our reading of literature? Terry Eagleton, one of the foremost critics of our generation, has some answers in this wonderfully clear and readable analysis. Sharp and concise, it is, without doubt, the most important work on literary criticism that has emerged out of the tradition of Marxist philosophy and social theory since the nineteenth century.',9780415285841,'[\'Literary Criticism\']',3,1,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=kUXXeSBNMx8C&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api','en'),(2508,'Children of God','[\'Mary Doria Russell\']','Ballantine Books','1999','A priest named Emilio Sandoz embarks on a quest to demystify God\'s providence that leads him to question the possibility of faith',9780449004838,'[\'Fiction\']',4,52,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=CyjUvQEACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api','en'),(2509,'When the Lion Feeds','[\'Wilbur Smith\']','Macmillan','2006-10-03','In late nineteenth-century South Africa, Sean Courteney follows his destiny to the gold mines of Pretoria, while his twin, Garrick, bitterly plots revenge against his brother for the shooting accident that crippled him. Reprint.',9780312940669,'[\'Fiction\']',4,5,'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=0YLT5DSlsgAC&printsec=f